**Product Requirements Document (PRD)**  
**Project Name:** X-FlapSaver – Realistic Airport Split-Flap + Matrix Screensaver  
**Version:** 1.1 (Revised)  
**Date:** 29 March 2026  
**Author:** Grok (xAI)  

### 1. Objective & Vision
Develop a **cross-platform “fake screensaver”** that **tops** the airport FlipFlap display shown in the referenced X post (https://x.com/ybhrdwj/status/2037110274696896687).  

The application must be **as realistic as possible**:
- **FlipFlap mode**: exact sequential forward-only rotation of each flap (no random flipping) + perfectly synchronized mechanical flip sound.
- **Matrix mode**: classic green digital rain with cryptic/Japanese/Katakana characters falling top-to-bottom, using the same X posts as data packets.
- Two clearly separated modes that can be switched **only via a setting inside the Screensaver-App** (not while the screensaver is running).
- All displayed information comes **exclusively from X** (real posts).
- The screensaver must interact with the **xai SDK or xai-API** (or any other compatible X API) using an API key supplied by the user.
- Per-mode configuration of specific X accounts, time window for fetching posts, and truncation length.
- Rotation through the latest posts; only the first **X characters** of each post are used.
- Data storage must be as simple as possible (e.g. a single `posts.json` file). No heavy infrastructure. Daily refresh is explicitly acceptable because “it is only a screensaver”.

The entire solution follows **exactly** the provided technical specification for a Tauri-based fake screensaver (no admin rights, no native .scr registration, user-space only).

### 2. Target Platforms
- **Primary**: Windows 11 (user-level execution, no admin rights)  
- **Secondary**: Linux (Ubuntu) – for development and testing, with functional parity where feasible.

### 3. Technology Stack (exactly as specified by user)
**Core Framework**  
- Tauri  

**Frontend**  
- HTML / CSS / JavaScript (**framework optional: Astro, or vanilla**)  

**Backend (Tauri Core)**  
- Rust (minimal usage; primarily for system integration such as idle detection and window management)

### 4. High-Level Architecture (exactly as in original spec)
```text
[ Idle Monitor Process ]
        ↓ (user inactive for N minutes)
[ Launch Screensaver App ]
        ↓
[ Fullscreen Overlay Window ]
        ↓ (user input detected)
[ Immediate Exit ]
```

Separation of concerns:
- Idle Monitor → launch
- Screensaver App → rendering + X data display

### 5. Functional Requirements (full coverage of user’s original points + spec)

#### 5.1 Idle Detection & Launch (unchanged from spec)
- System-wide inactivity (mouse + keyboard).
- Configurable timeout (default: 5 minutes).
- No admin privileges.
- Prevent multiple concurrent instances.

#### 5.2 Fullscreen & Exit Behavior (unchanged from spec)
- Borderless, always-on-top fullscreen overlay.
- Multi-monitor support (single spanning window or one window per display).
- Cursor hidden.
- Immediate exit on any keyboard input or mouse movement (configurable dead-zone).
- Clean state restoration.

#### 5.3 Autostart (user-level only)
- Windows: user Startup folder.
- Linux: `.config/autostart`.

#### 5.4 FlipFlap Mode (user’s core request)
- Visually identical to real airport split-flap boards.
- **Sequential forward-only rotation** of every single flap through its fixed character set until target character is reached.
- Mechanical flip sound **perfectly synchronized** to visual movement (multiple short samples + slight random pitch/volume for realism).
- Default board size: configurable rows × columns (example: 8×40).
- Content: latest X posts, truncated to user-configurable number of characters.
- Post rotation interval: configurable (default 15–30 seconds).

#### 5.5 Matrix Mode (user’s core request)
- Classic green-on-black digital rain.
- Falling characters: Katakana + Japanese + cryptic symbols.
- X posts appear as readable “data packets” within the rain stream.
- Same data source, truncation, and rotation logic as FlipFlap mode.

#### 5.6 Mode Switching
- Only possible via **settings inside the Screensaver-App**.
- Options: FlipFlap only, Matrix only, or Both (auto-switch every X minutes).

#### 5.7 X Data Integration (exactly as user described)
- Uses **xai SDK or xai-API** (or any compatible X API v2 endpoint).
- User supplies API key / Bearer token once (stored securely).
- **Per-mode configuration**:
  - Specific X accounts / search queries / list IDs.
  - Time window to consider (e.g. last 24 h, last 7 days).
  - Truncation: only first **X characters** per post.
- Fetching: daily refresh is sufficient; no real-time requirement.
- Storage: simplest possible – single `posts.json` file in app data folder (no database, no server).

#### 5.8 Settings UI (separate window)
- Mode selection.
- Per-mode X account / query / time-window / truncation settings.
- FlipFlap board size, rotation speed, sound volume.
- Matrix rain density, speed, glow.
- Idle timeout, mouse dead-zone.
- “Refresh Now” button for X data.

### 6. Non-Functional Requirements (exactly as in original spec)
- No admin rights whatsoever.
- Low CPU (<1 % idle monitor, <5 % screensaver).
- Stability on multi-monitor and resolution changes.
- Same codebase for Windows and Linux (platform-specific logic isolated).
- No crashes on rapid input/exit.

### 7. Out of Scope (unchanged)
- Native OS screensaver integration (.scr).
- System-level hooks requiring admin.
- Cloud sync, real-time streaming, complex backend.

### 8. Success Criteria
- FlipFlap rotation + sound are indistinguishable from real hardware.
- Matrix mode feels like the original film but powered by the user’s personal X feed.
- All original user conditions (Astro option, per-mode X config, JSON cache, daily fetch OK, etc.) are fully implemented.
- App behaves exactly like a native screensaver on Windows 11 while staying 100 % user-space.

